WEBVTT

NOTE
This file was generated by Descript <www.descript.com>

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.210
Are you considering a leaseback?

00:00:02.117 --> 00:00:06.017
A leaseback, also called a Seller’s
Temporary Lease, allows you to

00:00:06.017 --> 00:00:09.547
sell your home and remain in it
for a short period after closing.

00:00:10.327 --> 00:00:14.467
In Texas, this is handled using a
standardized lease agreement and

00:00:14.467 --> 00:00:16.627
is limited to no more than 60 days.

00:00:17.287 --> 00:00:19.747
Once the sale closes, you
are no longer the homeowner.

00:00:20.087 --> 00:00:23.227
You become a tenant, and the
buyer becomes your landlord.

00:00:23.957 --> 00:00:27.207
All terms are negotiated upfront,
including the length of the stay,

00:00:27.567 --> 00:00:31.277
daily rent, security deposit,
utilities, and the move out date.

00:00:32.750 --> 00:00:36.630
The buyer carries homeowner’s insurance
on the property, while you are required

00:00:36.630 --> 00:00:40.800
to carry renter’s insurance for your
personal belongings and liability.

00:00:42.050 --> 00:00:45.200
Rent and any security deposit
are typically paid at closing and

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:46.830
handled through the title company.

00:00:48.537 --> 00:00:52.917
It is important to understand that not all
buyers or their lenders allow leasebacks.

00:00:53.927 --> 00:00:58.567
Some lenders prohibit them entirely, and
some buyers need possession immediately.

00:00:59.237 --> 00:01:03.187
As a result, requiring a leaseback
will most likely limit your potential

00:01:03.187 --> 00:01:06.557
buyer pool and can prevent a
transaction from moving forward.

00:01:07.662 --> 00:01:10.972
A leaseback can be useful when
your next home is not ready or

00:01:10.972 --> 00:01:12.522
you need extra time to move.

00:01:12.952 --> 00:01:17.382
However, as a general rule, we discourage
sellers from requiring leasebacks

00:01:17.452 --> 00:01:19.122
unless they are truly necessary.

